'''Tsiklon''' (meaning [[cyclone]], {{lang-ru|'''Циклон'''}}) is the first Soviet [[satellite navigation system]], developed in the former [[Soviet Union]] and now operated by the [[Russian Space Forces]].
From 1967 to 1978 a total of 31 Tsiklon satellites were launched onboard [[Kosmos-3]] and [[Kosmos-3M]] rockets, from the [[Kapustin Yar]] and [[Plesetsk]] launch sites. The project was conceived in the 1950s and the draft proposal was approved in 1962, but was not made operational until 1972 due to delays.<ref name="tsi">[http://www.astronautix.com/craft/tsiklon.htm Tsiklon]</ref>
The successor satellites to Tsiklon were [[Parus (satellite)|Parus]] and [[Sfera (satellite)|Sfera]].<ref name="tsi" /> Currently, Russia operates the [[GLONASS]] system.
